One of the biggest mistakes people make in multicultural marketing is not knowing the actual hazards that exist for marginalized communities. 

What looks like a serene field to some is filled with landmines for others.  From #matthewshepard  to #ahmaudarbery  if brands are putting out the content without the understanding and the ideaoloogy of making the world a better, safer place, then they are missing the point.

Experience matters… People who have been there matter.

In this episode of the @socialstudiesshow @erictung gives me a real view of the #outdoor #fashion  #market with an Asian POV  and I dropped a few gems myself. 

Please educate yourself about 

www.matthewshepard.org/

www.ahmaudarberyfoundation.org/

#DONTSWEATTHETECHNIQUE. EP10  Here is a look back at @xavierjiminez1 in #LA for a test shoot. He took the time to share some pretty personal stories while we were shooting 

“I used to get in a lot of fights when I was younger. Kids would tease me about my freckles relentlessly. For a while I thought about bleaching them but now I’m glad I didn’t...”

” I’m glad you didn’t either. We celebrate the freaks and geeks around here and different is a beautiful badge of uniqueness. Everyone has their story to tell. “

#DONTSWEATTHETECHNIQUE. Ep11  Here is a look back at @lennytoussaint in #NYC.. well really Jersey City bit NYC sounds a lot cooler. It was at my buddy @davidshechter studio borrowing all of @monte_isom lights to work on some new lighting techiques.  One of the things I loved about new york was the photo community and the proximity to creative people that want you to succeed.  As we come into the holidays it makes me miss it a bit but also hopeful for new projects on the rise.  Looking to  collaborate with old friends. (i’m looking at you @mussoinc ) and making stuff that matters. I hope these photos bring you a bit of joy because even though I have that serious look on my face creating them (if you know me, you know I look like trying to solve a calculus problem on set ) It’s just because I’m trying my best and I’m smiling on the inside.  Happy Holidays

#DONTSWEATTHETECHNIQUE. Ep12 The key to shooting amazing scenics? Find clients that take you heliboarding. This was for a @dakine shoot years ago when my knees still had full fluidity and I could carry a small child on my back. I’m older and wiser now so I hire assistants for that. Anyone who wants to tell you how hardcore they are, or how much they had to endure to get the shot, let them have that. I’m happy to take an easy ride to the top and enjoy the view. This was probably one of the easiest shots I got during my stint in winter photography. Nature was just doing it’s thing and I took in the beauty. Hot tip for 2023.  Stop and enjoy the little moments. #newyearsresolutions

Today as we celebrate Dr. King it is a reminder that the struggle for equality isn’t an overnight change. It’s several small steps laying the foundation for people to be seen, heard and respected for their unique cultures. The camera gives me an opportunity to shine a light on different people and share their stories. Media and perspective matter and as Black man in America I take those things personally. I remind myself to listen just as much as I create and that often I am a conduit to someone else’s tale so I consistently check to try and get it right. Sometimes it’s the small details.  Things no one else can see, nuances of beauty and I’m able to share them through my lens. Remember Dr. King today and I’ll ask a small favor -  put his principles into your practice because every person has a dream and we can choose empathy and equity instead of oppression. MLK day isn’t just a holiday on a calendar. It’s an ideal we can practice everyday.

I was going to share this later but felt it was needed for today. Part of the ethos of #DEI shoots is trying to turn  negatives into positives. My perspective as a #Black photographer and having police security on a shoot is such a different trip than my counterparts. It’s  a bit uneasy as most people where I’m from are skeptical of law enforcement but my job is so much more than taking pictures. It’s making people feel seen and their stories told. Our patrolman had a deep understanding what we were doing and after we finished the job he made sure to comment saying he saw  how much effort, dedication and professionalism I was putting into my work. It kind of blew me away as I’ve been afraid of the police most of my life…. But in that moment I  realized my work is about building bridges, growing community and sometimes you don’t realize the impact until later. Just remember even in the dark days - there’s still a lot of people out there trying make a better world. It’s just putting another foot in front of the other on this journey called life. 
Love Stan ❤️

As we go into #BLACKHISTORYMONTH we come with hope and intention. Thinking culturally, creatively - taking up space and enjoying the moments. Our importance isn’t just relevant around a month or a day or a minute. Our worth is in our existence. The ability to chase any dream and do it with style, grace and exuberance. I see you today and everyday.

#DONTSWEATTHETECHNIQUE - EP #15 Here is a look back at a shoot that ran in @ironandair on a custom Ducati I shot. I love motorcycles and people so any chance I get to combine them I’m game.  This custom bike was so unique and it was random to find in a Brooklyn Coffee shop.  So I talked one of the owners from the shop to come and rip it around the streets of NYC for me.  A real run and gun situation with no real plan. Just thinking on my feet and using the environment. I love these kinds of shoots because it really tests spontaneity.

At 16, with a newly minted driver’s license in hand, I hit the road for an unforgettable cross-country adventure.  My father was transferred from Alaska to Virginia for work, and he thought it’d be a great father-son bonding experience to drive together. A summer on the road changed me forever. From the Alcan, to winding roads of the Rockies in Montana, across the plains of Oklahoma and into the nation’s capital in D.C., I fell in love. With the road. With shiny cars and thunderous motorcycles. With the grand beauty of these United States.

Before this trip, I didn’t appreciate the vastness of America or its diversity from communities to topography. But I learned that wheels could transport my sight and senses. That the open road was freedom personified.

Over the years, I have been on more road trips than I can count. Through my lens, from jobs to travel, I’ve captured interesting people and beautifully unique vehicles along the way. For this #BlackHistoryMonth, I’ve curated a collection of imagery that celebrates the #FreedomoftheRoad

Meeting people who have a unique way of seeing the world and have a gift for sharing with others is a rarity. When Dustin introduced himself to me and shared some of his work I was in awe. No Jacques Cousteau doc, no fast paced surf film, or scuba short had really captured the essence of the ocean and put it into a narrative that showed the beauty of the ocean. His videos  were welcoming and liberating. Completely counter to how most people perceive the relationship between Black people and water. During the 50 and 60’s due to Jim Crow laws, masses of the black community never learned how to swim because they didn’t have access to pools and that hurdle is still present due to that legacy perpetuating. I invited Dustin over for a short interview  because for Black History month I thought it was important to share his world underwater and encourage more people of color to enjoy the serenity of the sea. 

Check out more on Dustin #thecrenshawcrustacean

For those in the LA area Celes King III Aquatic Center is a brand new state of the art facility and they offer economical pricing for swim and surf lessons.🏊🏾‍♂️

#DONTSWEATTHETECHNIQUE - EP17 I have always been fascinated with the human body - it’s strength and  resilience and ,  It’s literally the strongest most complex machine known. Having worked with models and elite athletes I’m always surprised by the form, shape and contortions they can make with their bodies. They are always exemplified in the @ESPN body issue and I wanted to create something in that vein. While some find nudity shameful I consider it the freest form. If you haven’t seen it you should go watch “Somebody I Used to Know” with @alisonbrie and @jayrellis I won’t ruin it for you but it has some pretty comical moments about this.  @jenikajensen was game for an expression session and Joshua Tree provided the perfect backdrop to create  some memorable images.

For #womenshistorymonth I set out to create imagery that brings together fashion and technology in a way that illustrates THE FUTURE IS FEMALE. I had the opportunity to collaborate with @tiffencompany and used their Black Fog, Night Fog, and Star Filters to give the photography and video a unique, otherworldly glow. 

The compelling talent of Val Harvey’s makeup and Kait Lusk’s vision for styling came together to create the iconic looks you see here; looks that personify the essence of Afro Futurism through our model Alexis Turner 

In the behind the scenes video with Tiffen I discuss my love of Sci Fi and desire to spearhead even more projects that showcase the inevitable diverse and inclusive future.

HAPPY WOMEN’S HISTORY MONTH! This project has truly been one of my favorites. Lately I’ve been batting around the idea of what it means to be a strong woman. I’ve decided that term no longer serves me. I figured out that being strong only serves the narrative of those who prefer women, especially Black women, to remain in a place of lacking resources and being underserved to accomplish our goals when it ultimately doesn’t have to be that way. There was a time and place for strength, but there is no better time in history for women to move into our power. This shoot embodies power, beauty and femininity with an afro futuristic flare. Thank you to all of the incredible creatives who came together to bring this vision to life. I hope you enjoy it as much as we did producing! Stay tuned for images! #womenarepowerful #womenshistorymonth #blackgirlmagic #mohawkmakeup #afropunk #afrofuturism

The biggest testament to who we are is how we treat other people.

For #Pride month I thought it was worth stepping aside and asking someone in the #LGBTQ+ community what pride means for them. 

@toryscroggins shared these words with me 

“My art is all about self expression. As an actor I use to be afraid that opportunities would be limited to me if I showed the world the full spectrum of who I am, but one day I decided that I didn’t care anymore and that it was more important to me to be authentic than it was to be accepted. But once I made that decision I was shocked to see that more doors actually opened for me. The lesson that I learned from that was to be exactly who you are at all times because you are the representation of someone else out there who feels unseen. And that’s what being an artist is all about.”

#humanity

#automotivephotography #cars #photography #storytelling

What comes to mind when someone mentions a car club is usually older wealthy men meandering around a cars and coffee - talking horsepower, top speed, torque etc.  While it focuses on the rarity of the car it rarely highlights the uniqueness of the people. 

There is a barrier to entry and when you look at F1 racing and see that @lewishamilton is only on Black driver it couldn’t be more clear. But the streets are rooting for Lewis and looking at what he’s doing with the Hamilton Commission. Diverse car enthusiasts are figuring out how to apply that ethos at a more grassroots level.

With my Freedom of the Road series I ‘m been able to highlight more stories within the #Black community and our last one is @ryliczander and how he has be developing and outlet for the #LGBTQ+ community to share their enthusiasm and experience within the Auto Community with @ohshifttv 

As we took a ride with Rylic, he shared his favorite drive and perspective for this installment of #FreedomoftheRoad.

#BLACKICE A few years ago, I was commissioned by @snowboardermagazine to shoot the cover with @russellwinfield. While we navigated through many versions of art direction, my focus wasn’t solely on snowboarding but on capturing a compelling portrait that tells the story of being the first black professional snowboarder in a single image. Conducting research and drawing inspiration from amazing portrait photographers like @gordonparksfoundation and @nadavkander , I looked to their work for creative motivation.

The concept I developed involved a prop of frozen water over a pane of glass, symbolizing the melting away of barriers to reveal more of Russell’s face. Unfortunately, the glass was dropped as it was taken out of the freezer, but we managed to salvage a few broken pieces to shoot with, and I honestly think it might have enhanced the concept. These images didn’t make it into the interview, but they are my personal favorites. I’m sharing them now as they represent an interesting arc, showing where I came from and where I’m going.

It serves as a reminder that while we can appreciate the past, we should always be looking forward to progression.
